      "type": "paragraph",
      "id": "37ed48079c8fe377",
      "text": "Fuchs und Hoegl, „Die Schrift der Form. Peter Fuchs und Franz Hoegl über George Spencer-Browns Laws of Form“."
    },
    {
      "type": "paragraph",
      "id": "4b8276da2fb0d55a",
      "text": "Through the works of [[Gottlob Frege]] and [[Bertrand Russell]], logic had acquired an unprecedented diversity, and so it was expected that a suitable problem would be found for this impressive solution: the \"justifiable\" mathematics. As is well known, the reason-theoretical program of logicism created problems already at the beginning, to be fixed at the so-called Russell paradox of \"naive\" set theory (\"Does the set of all sets which do not contain themselves contain themselves?\")."
