        "id": "38facf3123699438",
        "text": "Russell's discovery initially put a stop to the completion of the logico-theoretical, set-theoretical justification of arithmetic, after Georg Cantor and Cesare Burali-Forti had already encountered the contradictions arising from negative self-referential constructions in set theory a few years earlier. At this point, the standard version of history switches to crisis rhetoric and dramatizing \"shock\" semantics. It is an interesting observation that the Laws of Form and its secondary literature also continue to write this dramaturgy. Admittedly, nothing of this can be traced in the texts of this period (cf. Mehrtens 1990: 150). The only one who could be \"shaken\" was Gottlob Frege himself. The news of Russell's paradox discovery - which was at the same time a paradox invention created by Frege's very own means - reached Frege by letter, as he states in his epilogue to the \"Grundgesetze der Arithmetik\" (Basic Laws of Arithmetic)"
