        "text": "The paradoxes of set theory discovered/generated at the turn of the century were initially not considered worthy of crisis beyond logicism, especially since these paradoxes could at least be brought under control to such an extent by the additional theory of type hierarchies that the (logicist) theory business could continue. Nevertheless, already in 1910, when Alfred Whitehead and Bertrand Russell published their Principa Mathematica (Whitehead/Russell 2008), not everyone was satisfied with the type theory proposed there; insofar, the paradoxes of set theory remained, if not crisis triggers, then certainly a strong stimulus to find other ways of dealing with these paradoxes – mostly, such as Ernst Zermelo's axiomatic set theory, as offers to prohibit paradoxes in more distinguished ways (cf. on this Lau 2005)."
